00:00:08.317 --> 00:00:09.484
- [Voiceover] So, Emily and I are here

00:00:09.484 --> 00:00:11.860
talking about Darwinism.

00:00:11.860 --> 00:00:13.260
I'm interested in Darwinism,

00:00:13.260 --> 00:00:16.299
because in the late 19th century,

00:00:16.299 --> 00:00:18.522
usually called the Gilded Age,

00:00:18.522 --> 00:00:21.929
there is a very prominent interpretation

00:00:21.929 --> 00:00:26.242
of Darwinism that is
called, Social Darwinism.

00:00:26.242 --> 00:00:30.706
Social Darwinism wasn't so
much an actual form of biology,

00:00:30.706 --> 00:00:33.802
as it was, kind of a misinterpretation

00:00:33.802 --> 00:00:38.065
of how natural selection and
the theory of evolution worked,

00:00:38.065 --> 00:00:41.011
that was used to justify or explain

00:00:41.011 --> 00:00:44.807
a lot of the social inequalities
of this time period.

00:00:44.807 --> 00:00:46.693
The way people often thought about it

00:00:46.693 --> 00:00:49.864
was that white Anglo-Saxon people,

00:00:49.864 --> 00:00:52.897
so Europeans, Northern Europeans,

00:00:52.897 --> 00:00:55.480
were kind of the most evolved.

00:00:56.688 --> 00:00:59.992
This is our timeline of evolution,

00:00:59.992 --> 00:01:02.909
from least evolved to most evolved,

00:01:04.033 --> 00:01:06.866
and people like African Americans,

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:11.383
or Asians, or Native Americans,

00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:16.127
or even Eastern Europeans,

00:01:18.234 --> 00:01:20.409
were less evolved.

00:01:20.409 --> 00:01:23.576
That they were on a scale of evolution

00:01:26.192 --> 00:01:30.592
where they hadn't come
as far as Anglo-Saxons.

00:01:30.592 --> 00:01:33.735
So, Emily, you're a biologist,

00:01:33.735 --> 00:01:35.761
and I would love to get your take

00:01:35.761 --> 00:01:39.184
on how it is that natural
selection actually works,

00:01:39.184 --> 00:01:41.344
and how this doesn't
quite describe what was

00:01:41.344 --> 00:01:42.618
really going on.

00:01:42.618 --> 00:01:44.514
- [Voiceover] Yeah, definitely.

00:01:44.514 --> 00:01:48.159
So, maybe I can speak first
to that specific graph

00:01:48.159 --> 00:01:50.048
that you've drawn on.

00:01:50.048 --> 00:01:52.042
I think that this is
actually a common point

00:01:52.042 --> 00:01:55.025
of confusion when it comes to evolution,

00:01:55.025 --> 00:01:57.163
that there's not really such a thing,

00:01:57.163 --> 00:02:00.178
as more or less evolved in evolution.

00:02:00.178 --> 00:02:02.403
So--
- [Voiceover] Okay, so,

00:02:02.403 --> 00:02:05.631
this gradient really doesn't exist.

00:02:05.631 --> 00:02:09.823
- [Voiceover] No, I mean,
there's sort of the,

00:02:09.823 --> 00:02:11.506
I think that people
sometimes see the pictures

00:02:11.506 --> 00:02:14.488
of like, the ape standing up,
and turning into a person,

00:02:14.488 --> 00:02:18.087
and they think, "Oh, this
is sort of a linear path

00:02:18.087 --> 00:02:20.409
"from one thing to another."

00:02:20.409 --> 00:02:24.576
What you really get is different
types of organisms evolving

00:02:25.542 --> 00:02:28.363
from a shared ancestor, and branching off.

00:02:28.363 --> 00:02:29.295
So--

00:02:29.295 --> 00:02:30.128
- [Voiceover] All right so--

00:02:30.128 --> 00:02:32.711
- [Voiceover] Nobody
who's alive on Earth today

00:02:32.711 --> 00:02:35.690
